data.title: Ant and Dec enjoy rare night out with their better halves at the TV BAFTA Awards 2015
data.meta_description: Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly enjoyed a rare night out with their better halves at the TV BAFTA Awards 2015, posing happily with their partners on the red carpet.
data.text:
Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly enjoyed a rare night out with their better halves at the TV BAFTA Awards 2015, posing happily with their partners on the red carpet.

Dressed in tuxedos, the dapper comedy duo beamed as they showed off their partners at the Theatre Royal in London on Sunday night.

Ant's wife Lisa Armstrong sported a black cocktail dress with cut-outs, while Dec's fiance Ali Astall wore a pleated gown of the same dark hue.

Scroll down for video

The presenters are rarely both seen with their partners, with their last public appearance as a foursome thought to be the Film BAFTA Awards in February.

Ant and Dec scooped two awards at the ceremony - Entertainment Programme and Entertainment Performers - and were sure to thank their leading ladies afterwards.

Speaking after accepting their second award for Entertainment Programme, Ant said: 'We love doing the shows, long may it continue.

'This is amazing, thanks girls, thanks very much for your support and love - let's go and get p****d!'

The long-term TV and music partners were thrilled to be picking up yet another gong for Saturday Night Takeaway in the Entertainment Programme category.

'Thank you very much! What a great start to the show... for us,' Ant said to the assembled audience while picking up the first award.

'We're delighted with it, really chuffed - this lot work so hard on it. We'll keep it short but thank you BAFTA, thank you to ITV, we're absolutely thrilled.'

Dec added: 'What a treat, what a treat this is. Have a lovely evening everybody. Thank you BAFTA!'

Meanwhile, although Ant and Dec were the only multiple winners on the night, one of the most poignant moments came when Coronation Street was revealed to have won the battle of the soap operas.

The ITV soap bagged the Soap & Continuing Drama gong beating out competition from their rivals, EastEnders, despite the BBC programme's intense 'who killed Lucy Beale?' storyline.

Producer Stuart Blackburn spoke for the cast and crew as he said: 'I'd like to dedicate this to my friend and colleague Anne Kirkbride.'

Actress Anne Kirkbride - famed for her role as Deirdre Barlow - passed away in January aged 60 following a battle with breast cancer.

The producer continued: 'Wow, really didn't see this one coming so thank you.

'To everyone in this category I know how hard you work. We produce some of the best moments on television.'

He also paid tribute to their soap rivals as he added: 'A big well done to EastEnders for getting through the live so well.

'It is solely about the team, everyone at Corrie, trying to make the best of everyday and make the best of everyone.'

Meanwhile, The Graham Norton Show was named Comedy & Comedy Entertainment Programme winner.

BAFTA host Graham was very pleased with his victory as he said: 'Really!? Thank you, that's very nice.

'Now, lots of the team are coming up. All I would say is we're all lucky here, we're nominees and in good things.

'But most of us have been in great big strinkers, turkeys so big they can't fit in a great big oven. But when you're in a stinker, you never blame yourself, it's never your fault you always say 'oh I don't know why they broadcast it then etc.'

He continued: 'So equally when you're in something good, it's nothing to do with you either. It's all these people.'

The top honours of the evening for solo awards went to Jason Watkins and Georgina Campbell.

Jason fended off the likes of Benedict Cumerbatch for Sherlock, Toby Jones for Marvellous and James Nesbitt in The Missing to win the Leading Actor title for the Lost Honour of Christopher Jefferies.

The drama tells the story of the retired school teacher who found himself at the centre of the Joanna Yeates murder investigation. The ITV show also won in the mini-series category.

'I'd like to congratulate all the nominees for their extraordinary performances,' he said, upon receipt of his gong.

'I'd like to thank my wife for putting up with me  I go away and come back a different person, I'm sorry I didn't come back taller and with more hair.

'I'd like to thank ITV for giving this drama a slot so that so many people could share Christopher's story. I'd like to thank Christopher himself - I'm sorry for invading in your life, this time we came with warm embrace and not with a bitter quill.

'Mr and Mrs Yeates for allowing us to have their daughter Joanna at the heart of this piece. I hope this was not too painful for them and (that) we can all now share in her memory.

'There is one person that I'd like to dedicate this award to and that's our daughter who we lost, funnily enough, just a few days after Joanna Yeates's death. If there is a reason why I am standing here it is because of our Maudey... so thank you.'

Georgina Campbell beat fellow Leading Actress nominees Keeley Hawes (Line of Duty), Sarah Lancashire (Happy Valley) and hot favourited Sheridan Smith (Cilla).

Campbell won for her portrayal of a victim of domestic abuse in the BBC Three drama Murdered by My Boyfriend.

'My mum is gonna kill me, she's been calling me all day asking me if I've written a speech and I said no because I'll never end up here,' she confessed as she picked up her BAFTA.

'This is insane, the women in this category are brilliant, brilliant actresses and if I have half the career they had in a few years I'll count myself very, very lucky.

'This award goes to everyone. It's easy to forget in the glitz and glamour that this was about domestic abuse which happens to women every day and this was about a real girl who did die so I want to say thank you to Ashley's very real family and friends who gave us so much. They're brilliant and very brave people, it's a credit to them and to Ashley so... thank you.'

W1A actress Jessica Hynes was the Female Performance in a Comedy Programme Winner, while Matt Berry bagged the Male Performance in a Comedy Programme for his role in Toast of London.

Jessica who won her award for playing Siobhan Sharpe in the drama told the audience to rapturous applause: 'I'm from a single parent family. I'm really worried about the cuts that are coming in state education and to people in low income families.

'Because I don't feel low income means low talent, low imagination or low intelligence,' she added.

Meanwhile, Matt added: 'Good god, I certainly didn't expect this to happen. I've got to pay tribute to the other nominees who are all fantastic.

I kind of came in through the back door so this is kind of something else. I was very, very lucky to work with the best. I've been very, very lucky. Toast is not just me obviously, mainly Channel 4 because no one really makes those kind of shows anymore.

'More than anything I want to thank my mum and Dad, they've had a roughish time this year. So this is for them. Thanks very much indeed.'

The Supporting Actress title went to Gemma Jones for her portrayal of Mary Baldwin in Marvellous.

The bio-pic told the true story of Neil Baldwin, who refused to accept the limitations of his learning disability.

It was her first nomination for the veteran actress since 1997. She told the audience: 'I'd like to thank the real Neil who so generously allowed us to intrude on his extraordinary life.'

Stephen Rea won Supporting Actor for his role in the political thriller The Honourable Woman.

'Thank you BAFTA, sometimes you get to work with a great director and a great writer and sometimes a great producer. Then you get to work with Hugo Blick who is all three of those thing,' he said, praising the show's writer and director.

'All the cast and crew were magnificent. There were so many wonderful actors in the honourable woman, I feel I am receiving this on their behalf. '

Life And Death Row nabbed the gong for Factual Series while the Single Documentary award went to The Paedophile Hunter.

The Specialist Factual Winner award went to Grayson Perry: Who Are You?, while daredevil Bear Grylls nabbed the prize for Reality & Constructed Factual for his hit Channel 4 desert island series The Island.

Sky New Live At Five: Ebola was named best New Coverage show, while the award for Best Current Affairs programme went to Children On The Frontline (Dispatches).

Matthew McConaughey's popular US drama, True Detective, received the International award, while British producer and writer Jeff Pope was honoured with the Special Award.

Jeff Pope, the writer of Cilla, won the coveted Alan Clarke award - named in honour of the late director.

'Thank you. Thank you very much. Thank you to Steve, thank you to BAFTA and to all my colleagues and friends this is a real honour, overwhelming really. Given that this award commemorates Alan Clarke I did wonder if for tonight at least I can get to say that I'm the 'Guvna'. Alan knows what I'm talking about.

'Thank you ITV for nurturing me throughout my career. I wrote Philomena with Steve [Coogan] and I wrote a whole load of new things so thank you. I've had the great good luck to work with some marvellously talented people. To finish I'd like to simply say that in this industry it's not what I've made but who I've made it with that really matters to me so thank you to all of them and hello mum.'

Grand Designs presenter Kevin McCloud thanked the 'millions and millions of loyal fans' who have followed the Channel 4 programme 'for the past 20 years' as he collected the award for Best Feature

'Thank you BAFTA, I'm gobsmacked,' he said. 'We've often described ourselves as the BAFTA bridesmaids but never the bride so thank you.

'Thank you to Channel 4 who commissioned it back in 1994... Not least to the millions and millions and millions of people who have been loyal to the series for the past 25 years so thank you all.'

Channel 4 stalwart Jon Snow was given the top honour of the night, as he proudly took to the stage to receive the BAFTA Fellowship title.

The newsreader gave a typically affable and quip-heavy speech up on the stage, before posing up a treat with his shiny gold prize afterwards.

'I didn't think I and Coronation Street would forge a bond tonight, but we have,' he said. 'We're both team operations.'

The news correspondent, who was honoured in recognition of his career spanning 40 years, added: 'We are living in the Golden Age of journalism.
